### Patient Summary
This 53-year-old female with a history of primary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC) and cirrhosis (Child-Pugh B, MELD 12) presented with a recurrence of right upper quadrant (RUQ) abdominal pain and fever (100.7°F). Her symptoms occurred while she was on day five of an outpatient course of Ertapenem for a previous episode of cholangitis. On admission, RUQ ultrasound and MRCP confirmed cirrhosis and portal hypertension (splenomegaly, ascites, varices) and suggested biliary sludge or stones in the distal common bile duct and cystic duct remnant. An ERCP was performed, identifying marked intrahepatic ductal narrowing consistent with PSC and successfully removing biliary sludge. An EGD performed during the same admission identified an 8 mm clean-based ulcer at the gastroesophageal junction and portal gastropathy. Given her history of multidrug-resistant cholangitis, she was transitioned from Ertapenem to Meropenem. The patient showed significant clinical improvement post-intervention and remained afebrile. She was discharged in stable condition to complete a 7-day course of IV Meropenem via her existing PICC line with instructions for follow-up laboratory monitoring and outpatient transplant clinic follow-up.

### Past Medical History
- Primary sclerosing cholangitis (PSC)
- Recurrent cholangitis requiring multiple hospitalizations
- Cirrhosis (Child-Pugh B, MELD 12) with portal hypertension, ascites, hepatic encephalopathy, and esophageal varices (s/p prior banding)
- Celiac sprue
- Hypertension
- GERD
- Hypothyroidism
- Obstructive sleep apnea (OSA)
- Questionable Crohn\'s disease
- Depression

